 :tx/provenance :observed
 :tx/rationale "DS-COMMIT: Group commit thread — batch multiple agents' writes into single fsync. Inspired by FrankenSQLite's WriteCoordinator and PostgreSQL's commit_delay. ARCHITECTURE: A single commit thread owns the write lock. Agent requests arrive via an mpsc channel. The thread drains the channel every 5-50ms (adaptive: shorter under load, longer when idle). For each batch: (1) Assign TxIds monotonically (atomic increment per write). (2) Acquire exclusive write lock on Store. (3) apply_datoms for all transactions in the batch (O(k*log N) total where k=datoms in batch). (4) Release write lock. (5) Append all WAL entries in single write() call. (6) Single fsync() for entire batch. (7) Notify all waiting CLIs via oneshot channels. PERFORMANCE: At 50 agents × 1 write/s = 50 writes/s. With 50ms batch window: ~2.5 writes/batch average. Instead of 50 fsyncs/s, ~20 fsyncs/s. At 500 agents: ~25 writes/batch, ~20 fsyncs/s (fsync count is O(1/batch_interval), not O(agents)). VISIBILITY: Datoms are visible in-memory BEFORE fsync completes. The CLI can optionally wait for fsync (DurabilityPermit pattern from asupersync) or return after visibility (faster but less durable)."
